<p class="p">From the study of Crapiste and Rotstein [
 <xref rid="B9-foods-08-00191" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">9</xref>], 
 <disp-formula class="disp-formula">a
  <sub class="sub">w g</sub> = X
  <sub class="sub">g</sub> × 10^(−0.858*(1 − X
  <sub class="sub">g</sub>)^2.0
  <label class="label">(3)</label>
 </disp-formula>
 <disp-formula class="disp-formula">a
  <sub class="sub">w s</sub> = X
  <sub class="sub">s</sub> × 10^(−2.772*(1 − X
  <sub class="sub">s</sub>))^2.0
  <label class="label">(4)</label>
 </disp-formula>
 <disp-formula class="disp-formula">a
  <sub class="sub">w a</sub> = X
  <sub class="sub">a</sub> × 10^(−0.716*(1 − X
  <sub class="sub">a</sub>)^2.0
  <label class="label">(5)</label>
 </disp-formula>where X
 <sub class="sub">g</sub>, X
 <sub class="sub">s</sub> and X
 <sub class="sub">a</sub> are the water mole fractions of glucose, sucrose, and ashes.
</p>
